Coding club on ggplot2

In this coding club, we are going to uncover all the secrets of ggplot2. If you’ve ever been frustrated with making beautiful visualizations in R, you’re in the right place! We’re here to take you on a journey, from the basics of ggplot2 to advanced techniques, ensuring you learn everything you need to bring your data to life visually.

There are 4 main parts to this coding club * Introduction * Basics & highlights with short exercises * Issues * Two advanced exercises from scratch * Dataset from the London firebrigade on number of rescues of animals over the years * Dataset from 3 species of penguins in the Antarctic region

The ggplot2 library and its close friends…

Practicing Basics & highlights

orange_data = force(Orange) # dataset on growth of orange trees (Tree ID - days old - circumference)
orange_data$Tree = factor(orange_data$Tree, levels = c("1", "2", "3", "4", "5")) # TO DO: stap verduidelijken

1. Basic aesthetics in a simple scatter plot

# 1.1 make a basic point graph with age and circumference
ggplot(orange_data, aes(x = age, y = circumference)) +
  geom_point()

# 1.2 add color to the points according to the age
ggplot(orange_data, aes(x = age, y = circumference, color = age)) + # changing colors according to a variable
  geom_point()                                                      #  -> within aes()

# 1.3 color all the points in orange
ggplot(orange_data, aes(x = age, y = circumference)) +              # all data same color -> outside aes()
  geom_point(color = "orange")

# 1.4 add color to the points according to the tree ID & shape the points like a cross
ggplot(orange_data, aes(x = age, y = circumference, color = Tree)) +
  geom_point(shape=4)

2. Basic geometries & facets

# 2.1 add a smoother to the scatterplot
ggplot(orange_data, aes(x = age, y = circumference)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

# 2.2 make a boxplot of the lengths of the trees per age, colored
orange_data$age_categorical<-factor(orange_data$age) # transform the ages into a categorical variable
ggplot(orange_data, aes(x = age_categorical, y = circumference, fill = age)) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(group = age_categorical))

# 2.3 facet the point graph into a plot for each tree 
ggplot(orange_data, aes(x = age, y = circumference, color = Tree)) +
  geom_point() + 
  facet_wrap(~Tree) 

# 2.4 zoom in on age = 118
ggplot(orange_data, aes(x = age, y = circumference, color = Tree)) +
  geom_point() + 
  facet_zoom(y=age_categorical=='484')

3. Basic statistics

# 3.1 make a barplot with average circumference per age, EXTRA: add a label above each bar
ggplot(orange_data, aes(x = age_categorical, y = circumference))+
  geom_bar(stat='summary')+ # stat='summary' calculates several statistics, the mean is default
  geom_text(aes(label = after_stat(y)), stat='summary', vjust = -0.5) #vjust adjusts the position of the labels vertically
## No summary function supplied, defaulting to `mean_se()`
## No summary function supplied, defaulting to `mean_se()`

#3.2 smoother with lm
ggplot(orange_data, aes(x=age, y=circumference))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth(method='lm')
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

#3.3 smoother with
ggplot(orange_data, aes(x=age, y=circumference, colour = Tree))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth(method='lm')
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

4. Coordinates, themes, color palettes

# 4.1 make the following barplot horizontally
ggplot(orange_data, aes(x = age_categorical, y = circumference))+
  geom_bar(stat='summary')+ 
  geom_text(aes(label = after_stat(y)), stat='summary', hjust = -0.1)+
  coord_flip()
## No summary function supplied, defaulting to `mean_se()`
## No summary function supplied, defaulting to `mean_se()`

# 4.2 add a theme (eg. bw, minimal ...) to the following linear regression
ggplot(orange_data, aes(x = age, y = circumference, color = Tree)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  theme_classic() 
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

# 4.3 add a personalized color palette for the trees (e.g. wes anderson)
ggplot(orange_data, aes(x = age, y = circumference, color = Tree)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  theme_classic() +
  scale_color_manual(values = wes_palette("Cavalcanti1", 5, type = "discrete"))
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

# 4.4 add a title to the point graph and change colors per tree into an RColorBrewer color palette
ggplot(orange_data, aes(x = age, y = circumference, color = Tree)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  theme_classic() +
  scale_color_manual(values = wes_palette("Cavalcanti1", 5, type = "discrete"))+
  labs(title = "Relationship between the age of a tree (days) and its circumference (cm)")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Advanced exercises

Dataset 1: rescues of animals in London by the firebrigade***

# Some data cleaning first
rescues = read_xlsx("./animal_rescues_UK.xlsx")
rescues$time = as.Date(rescues$date_time_of_call, format = "%d/%m/%Y %H:%M")
rescues$time_char = as.character(rescues$time)
rescues_tidy = rescues %>% separate(time_char, sep = "-", into = c("year", "month", "day")) %>%
  dplyr::select(-c(1, 13, 14))

Try to VISUALIZE the answers to the following questions:

1.1 In what years do we find the most rescues for dogs, cats and foxes and deer?

  • point + line plot (x = time, y = number of rescues)
  • faceting per animal

FANCY EXTRAS - with a font - personalized color palette, for every animal

# first some tidying, extracting only the data of the animals that we want
rescues_number = rescues_tidy %>% filter(animal_group_parent == "Cat" | animal_group_parent == "Dog" | animal_group_parent == "Deer" | animal_group_parent == "Fox") %>%
  group_by(year, animal_group_parent) %>% # counting the number of rescues per animal
  summarise(Rescues = n())

#basic solution
plot1_1<-ggplot(rescues_number, aes(x = as.numeric(year), y = Rescues, color = animal_group_parent)) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_line(size = 1) +
  labs(x = "Year") +
  facet_wrap(~animal_group_parent, scales = "free") +
  theme_classic() 
plot1_1

#fancy solution
plot1_1_fancy<-plot1_1 +
  theme(text = element_text(family = "ggfont", size = 30), 
        plot.background = element_rect(fill = "white"), panel.background = element_rect(fill = "lightgrey"),
        legend.position="none") +
  scale_color_manual(values = wes_palette("Zissou1", 4, type = "discrete"))
plot1_1_fancy

1.2 When do most rescues take place during the year? Is this different for domestic animals (cat, dog) vs. wildlife (deer, fox)?

  • density plot (density of rescues for every animal throughout the year)

FANCY EXTRA - with a font - personalized color palette, for every animal - gganimate: show one density plot at the time and switch the species every two seconds

rescues_2010 = rescues_tidy %>% 
  filter(year == 2010) %>% 
  filter(animal_group_parent == "Cat" | animal_group_parent == "Dog" | animal_group_parent == "Deer" | animal_group_parent == "Fox")

#basic solution
plot1_2<-ggplot(rescues_2010, aes(x = time, fill =  animal_group_parent)) + 
  geom_density() + 
  theme_classic() +
  labs(y = "Rescues (%)")
plot1_2 + facet_grid(~animal_group_parent)

# fancy solution
plot1_2_fancy<-plot1_2+
  theme(text = element_text(family = "ggfont", color = "black", size = 30), legend.position = "none", 
        plot.background = element_rect(fill = "white"), panel.background = element_rect(fill = "lightgrey")) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = wes_palette("Zissou1", 4, type = "discrete")) +
  transition_states(animal_group_parent,
                    transition_length = 2,
                    state_length = 1) + ease_aes('cubic-in-out') + ggtitle("{closest_state}")
plot1_2_fancy

1.3 What is the proportion of rescues of cats, dogs, horses, birds, foxes, deer, throughout the years? Does this change?

  • stream graph

FANCY EXTRAS - with a font - personalized color palette, for every animal

rescues_dist =  rescues_tidy %>% 
  filter(!grepl("Unknown", animal_group_parent)) %>%
  filter(animal_group_parent == "Cat" | animal_group_parent == "Dog" | animal_group_parent == "Bird" | animal_group_parent == "Fox" | animal_group_parent == "Deer" | animal_group_parent == "Horse") %>%
  group_by(year, animal_group_parent) %>%
  summarise(Rescues = n())

#basic solution
plot1_3<-ggplot(rescues_dist, aes(x = as.numeric(year), y = Rescues, fill = animal_group_parent)) + 
  geom_stream(type = "proportional") +
  labs(x = "Year", title = "Proportion of rescues from 2009 to 2021") +
  theme_classic()
plot1_3

#fancy solution
pal = wes_palette("Zissou1", length(unique(rescues_dist$animal_group_parent)), type = "continuous")
plot1_3_fancy<-plot1_3+
  theme(text = element_text(family = "ggfont", color = "black", size = 30), legend.position = "bottom", 
        plot.background = element_rect(fill = "white"), panel.background = element_rect(fill = "lightgrey")) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = pal)
plot1_3_fancy

1.4 In what area in London do we find the most rescues for cats?

  • bar plot, with labels

FANCY EXTRAS - with a font - personalized color palette, for every animal

rescues_cat = rescues_tidy %>% 
  filter(animal_group_parent == "Cat") %>%
  group_by(borough) %>%
  summarise(Rescues = n())

# basic solution
plot1_4<-ggplot(na.omit(rescues_cat), aes(x = reorder(borough, -Rescues), y = Rescues, fill = borough)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  geom_text(aes(label = Rescues), hjust=0.0, size = 6) +
  labs(x = "borough", y = "rescues", title = "Rescues in every borough") +
  theme_classic()+
  coord_flip()
plot1_4

# fancy solution
pal = wes_palette("Zissou1", length(unique(rescues_cat$borough)), type = "continuous")

plot1_4_fancy<-plot1_4 +
  theme(text = element_text(family = "ggfont", color = "black", size = 30), legend.position = "none", 
        plot.background = element_rect(fill = "white"), panel.background = element_rect(fill = "lightgrey")) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = pal) 
plot1_4_fancy

Try to VISUALIZE the answers to the following questions

2.1 What are the distributions of the morphological traits? (violin plot)

penguins_long = penguins %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c("bill_length_mm", "bill_depth_mm", "flipper_length_mm", "body_mass_g"), names_to = "trait", values_to = "trait_value")

ggplot(penguins_long, aes(x = trait, y  = trait_value, fill = trait)) +
  #geom_boxplot() +
  geom_violin() +
  geom_jitter(size = 0.5, alpha = 0.5, height = 0, width = 0.1) +
  theme_classic() +
  facet_wrap(~trait, scales = "free") +
  theme(text = element_text(family = "penguin", size = 40), legend.position = "none",
        plot.background = element_rect(fill = "white"), panel.background = element_rect(fill = "lightskyblue3")) +
  labs(y = "trait value", title = "Morphological traits") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = wes_palette("Cavalcanti1", 4, type = "discrete"))

2.2 Are there relationships between the morphological traits? And is there a sex difference? (point graph, with linear regression line)

penguins_sex = penguins %>% filter(sex == "male" | sex == "female")
ggplot(penguins_sex, aes(x = bill_length_mm, y = bill_depth_mm, color = sex, shape = sex)) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", aes(group = sex)) +
  theme_classic() +
  theme(text = element_text(family = "penguin", size = 40), legend.position = "bottom",
        plot.background = element_rect(fill = "white"), panel.background = element_rect(fill = "lightskyblue3")) +
  labs() +
  scale_color_manual(values = wes_palette("Cavalcanti1", 2, type = "discrete"))
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

ggplot(penguins_sex, aes(y = flipper_length_mm, x = body_mass_g, color = sex, shape = sex)) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", aes(group = sex)) +
  theme_classic() +
  theme(text = element_text(family = "penguin", size = 40), legend.position = "bottom",

2.3 How do the species differ in body weight? Is there a sex effect? (box plot, 2 factors)

ggplot(penguins_sex, aes(x = species, y = body_mass_g, fill = sex)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  theme_classic() +
  theme(text = element_text(family = "penguin", size = 40), legend.position = "bottom",
        plot.background = element_rect(fill = "white"), panel.background = element_rect(fill = "lightskyblue3")) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = wes_palette("Cavalcanti1", 2, type = "discrete"))

2.4 Did the body weight change over the years? Is there a difference between species? (boxplot, facet)

ggplot(penguins, aes(x = as.factor(year), y = body_mass_g, fill = species)) +
  geom_boxplot( alpha = 0.8) +
  facet_wrap(~species) +
  theme_classic() +
  scale_fill_manual(values = wes_palette("Cavalcanti1", 3, type = "discrete")) +
  geom_smooth(aes(group = species), color = "black", se = T) +
  labs(x = "Year") +
  theme(text = element_text(family = "penguin", size = 40), legend.position = "none", 
        plot.background = element_rect(fill = "white"), panel.background = element_rect(fill = "lightskyblue3"))

2.5 What is the overall correlation between all traits measured? (correlation matrix)

penguins_corr = na.omit(penguins %>% select(c(3:6))) # only the numeric traits, no NA's
corr <- round(cor(penguins_corr), 2)
head(corr)
##                   bill_length_mm bill_depth_mm flipper_length_mm body_mass_g
## bill_length_mm              1.00         -0.24              0.66        0.60
## bill_depth_mm              -0.24          1.00             -0.58       -0.47
## flipper_length_mm           0.66         -0.58              1.00        0.87
## body_mass_g                 0.60         -0.47              0.87        1.00
melted_corr <- melt(corr)

ggplot(melted_corr, aes(x = Var1, y = Var2, fill = value)) +
  geom_tile() +
  geom_text(aes(label = value), color = "black", size = 8) +
  labs(x = "Variable 1", y = "Variable 2", title = "Correlation matrix") +
  theme_classic() +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "white", high = "darkorange") +
  theme(text = element_text(family = "penguin", size = 40), legend.position = "left", 
        plot.background = element_rect(fill = "white"), panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white"))
